{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01GAJJ4E5B8RRmeHUTTrGDDL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import lombok.Getter;\n     4→import lombok.Setter;\n     5→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.tag.Tag;\n     6→\n     7→import java.util.List;\n     8→import java.util.stream.Collectors;\n     9→\n    10→@Getter\n    11→@Setter\n    12→public class TagsResponse {\n    13→\n    14→    private List<String> tags;\n    15→\n    16→    public TagsResponse(List<Tag> tags) {\n    17→        this.tags = tags.stream().map(Tag::getName).collect(Collectors.toList());\n    18→    }\n    19→}\n    20→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"4cfa10e2-8df8-4987-aba1-27affac7e04f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01LArkCGLSsgxEp9qryiRkXJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     4→import lombok.Getter;\n     5→import lombok.NoArgsConstructor;\n     6→import lombok.Setter;\n     7→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.user.User;\n     8→\n     9→@Getter\n    10→@Setter\n    11→@NoArgsConstructor\n    12→@JsonRootName(\"user\")\n    13→public class UserResponse {\n    14→\n    15→    private String username;\n    16→    private String bio;\n    17→    private String image;\n    18→    private String email;\n    19→    private String token;\n    20→\n    21→    public UserResponse(User user, String token) {\n    22→        this.username = user.getUsername();\n    23→        this.bio = user.getBio();\n    24→        this.image = user.getImage();\n    25→        this.email = user.getEmail();\n    26→        this.token = token;\n    27→    }\n    28→}\n    29→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"94e4126b-8cc1-48e4-a338-cc81a6691f1f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01GUJGmgWZ8w8XngKivDKRrD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.resource.utils;\n     2→\n     3→import org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response.*;\n     4→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.feature.*;\n     5→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.Article;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.PageResult;\n     7→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.comment.Comment;\n     8→import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;\n     9→import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;\n    10→\n    11→import java.util.List;\n    12→import java.util.UUID;\n    13→import java.util.stream.Collectors;\n    14→\n    15→@Service\n    16→public class ResourceUtils {\n    17→\n    18→    private static final int DEFAULT_LIMIT = 20;\n    19→    @Autowired\n    20→    private FindUserByUsername findUserByUsername;\n    21→    @Autowired\n    22→    private IsFollowingUser isFollowingUser;\n    23→    @Autowired\n    24→    private FindArticleTags findArticleTags;\n    25→    @Autowired\n    26→    private IsArticleFavorited isArticleFavorited;\n    27→    @Autowired\n    28→    private ArticleFavoritesCount articleFavoritesCount;\n    29→\n    30→    public ProfileResponse profileResponse(String username, UUID loggedUserId) {\n    31→        final var user = findUserByUsername.handle(username);\n    32→        final var profileResponse = new ProfileResponse(user);\n    33→        if (loggedUserId != null) {\n    34→            profileResponse.setFollowing(isFollowingUser.handle(loggedUserId, user.getId()));\n    35→        }\n    36→        return profileResponse;\n    37→    }\n    38→\n    39→    public ArticleResponse articleResponse(Article article, UUID loggedUserId) {\n    40→        final var author = article.getAuthor();\n    41→        final var profileResponse = profileResponse(author.getUsername(), author.getId());\n    42→        final var tags = findArticleTags.handle(article);\n    43→        final var favoritesCount = articleFavoritesCount.handle(article.getId());\n    44→        final var articleResponse = new ArticleResponse(article, profileResponse, favoritesCount, tags);\n    45→        if (loggedUserId != null) {\n    46→            articleResponse.setFavorited(isArticleFavorited.handle(article, loggedUserId));\n    47→        }\n    48→        return articleResponse;\n    49→    }\n    50→\n    51→    public ArticlesResponse articlesResponse(PageResult<Article> pageResult, UUID loggedUserId) {\n    52→        final var resultResponse = pageResult.getResult().stream().map(article -> articleResponse(article, loggedUserId)).collect(Collectors.toList());\n    53→        return new ArticlesResponse(resultResponse, pageResult.getTotal());\n    54→    }\n    55→\n    56→    public CommentResponse commentResponse(Comment comment, UUID loggedUserId) {\n    57→        final var commentAuthor = comment.getAuthor();\n    58→        final var authorResponse = profileResponse(commentAuthor.getUsername(), loggedUserId);\n    59→        return new CommentResponse(comment, authorResponse);\n    60→    }\n    61→\n    62→    public CommentsResponse commentsResponse(List<Comment> comments, UUID loggedUserId) {\n    63→        final var resultResponse = comments.stream().map(comment -> commentResponse(comment, loggedUserId)).collect(Collectors.toList());\n    64→        return new CommentsResponse(resultResponse);\n    65→    }\n    66→\n    67→    public int getLimit(int limit) {\n    68→        return limit > 0 ? limit : DEFAULT_LIMIT;\n    69→    }\n    70→}\n    71→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"7b6303de-3b25-42ea-a661-cc1f9d34d6be"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01UMbYwMh2fnQ7amimi5xy5s","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.infrastructure.config;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.DeserializationFeature;\n     4→import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;\n     5→import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.SerializationFeature;\n     6→import com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype.jsr310.JavaTimeModule;\n     7→import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;\n     8→import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;\n     9→import org.springframework.context.annotation.Primary;\n    10→\n    11→@Configuration\n    12→public class SerializerConfig {\n    13→\n    14→    @Bean\n    15→    @Primary\n    16→    public ObjectMapper objectMapper() {\n    17→        ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();\n    18→        objectMapper.enable(SerializationFeature.WRAP_ROOT_VALUE);\n    19→        objectMapper.enable(DeserializationFeature.UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE);\n    20→        objectMapper.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());\n    21→        return objectMapper;\n    22→    }\n    23→\n    24→    @Bean(\"noWrapObjectMapper\")\n    25→    public ObjectMapper noWrapRootValueObjectMapper() {\n    26→        return new ObjectMapper().registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());\n    27→    }\n    28→}\n    29→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"40c039d5-4aca-490b-a032-9da4e35a3618"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_018A3CcgQfFBuamoC2TVb7Vc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I can see the issues clearly:\n\n1. **WRAP_ROOT_VALUE issue**: The primary ObjectMapper has `WRAP_ROOT_VALUE` enabled, which means `TagsResponse` gets serialized as `{\"TagsResponse\": {\"tags\": [...]}}` instead of `{\"tags\": [...]}`. Similarly, `ArticlesResponse` gets wrapped. The `UserResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"user\")` which works for that, but `TagsResponse` and `ArticlesResponse` don't have root names.\n\n2. **Request deserialization**: With `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE` enabled, Spring expects the request body to have a root wrapper name. The request wrappers already handle this, but there might be issues with how they're defined.\n\nLet me check the request wrapper models and other response models."}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3120,"cache_read_input_tokens":46312,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3120,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":404},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"15abae41-3037-413a-8a81-d10e28d65ff3"}
