{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_019px1FqQ6LUUfkTMejWCUQe","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonFormat;\n     4→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     5→import lombok.Getter;\n     6→import lombok.NoArgsConstructor;\n     7→import lombok.Setter;\n     8→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.article.Article;\n     9→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.tag.Tag;\n    10→\n    11→import java.time.LocalDateTime;\n    12→import java.util.List;\n    13→import java.util.stream.Collectors;\n    14→\n    15→@Getter\n    16→@Setter\n    17→@NoArgsConstructor\n    18→@JsonRootName(\"article\")\n    19→public class ArticleResponse {\n    20→\n    21→    private String slug;\n    22→    private String title;\n    23→    private String description;\n    24→    private String body;\n    25→    private List<String> tagList;\n    26→\n    27→    @JsonFormat(shape = JsonFormat.Shape.STRING, pattern = \"yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss.SSS'Z'\")\n    28→    private LocalDateTime createdAt;\n    29→\n    30→    @JsonFormat(shape = JsonFormat.Shape.STRING, pattern = \"yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss.SSS'Z'\")\n    31→    private LocalDateTime updatedAt;\n    32→\n    33→    private boolean favorited;\n    34→    private long favoritesCount;\n    35→    private ProfileResponse author;\n    36→\n    37→    public ArticleResponse(\n    38→            Article article, ProfileResponse author, long favoritesCount, List<Tag> tags) {\n    39→        this.slug = article.getSlug();\n    40→        this.title = article.getTitle();\n    41→        this.description = article.getDescription();\n    42→        this.body = article.getBody();\n    43→        this.createdAt = article.getCreatedAt();\n    44→        this.updatedAt = article.getUpdatedAt();\n    45→        this.author = author;\n    46→        this.favoritesCount = favoritesCount;\n    47→        this.tagList = tags.stream().map(Tag::getName).collect(Collectors.toList());\n    48→    }\n    49→}\n    50→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"aeb135e9-b3cb-4aa1-bf0e-c1850717acf4"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01Whgu1mV5CgzuCDhWPuuaHp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand all the issues. The root problem is the `WRAP_ROOT_VALUE` / `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE` configuration on the primary ObjectMapper. Here's what's happening:\n\n1. **Tags/Articles response**: `TagsResponse` doesn't have `@JsonRootName`, so with `WRAP_ROOT_VALUE`, it gets serialized as `{\"TagsResponse\": {\"tags\": [...]}}` instead of `{\"tags\": [...]}`. Same with `ArticlesResponse`.\n\n2. **User registration 400**: With `UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE` enabled, Spring's Jackson deserialization tries to unwrap the root. But the request body `{\"user\": {\"username\": ..., \"email\": ..., \"password\": ...}}` is being deserialized into `NewUserRequestWrapper` which already has a `user` field. The unwrapping adds another level - it expects `{\"NewUserRequestWrapper\": {\"user\": {...}}}`.\n\nThe fix is to **remove WRAP_ROOT_VALUE/UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE from the primary ObjectMapper** since the response models already handle wrapping through their structure (e.g., `ArticlesResponse` has `articles` field, `UserResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"user\")`). The models that need root wrapping (like `UserResponse`, `ArticleResponse`) use `@JsonRootName`, but for collections they're already wrapped manually.\n\nActually wait - the issue is more nuanced. `UserResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"user\")` which means with `WRAP_ROOT_VALUE` it becomes `{\"user\": {\"username\": ...}}`. But `TagsResponse` would become `{\"TagsResponse\": {\"tags\": ...}}`. And the request wrappers like `NewUserRequestWrapper` already contain a `user` field.\n\nThe correct approach: **Disable WRAP_ROOT_VALUE/UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE globally** and use the wrapper classes for both requests and responses. For responses that need a root name (like `UserResponse` with `@JsonRootName(\"user\")`), we need to manually wrap them.\n\nLet me also check the remaining response models:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3460,"cache_read_input_tokens":50233,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3460,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":934},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"df1561a9-af26-4e6c-a6ca-e235ecd783f5","uuid":"61cb1e99-6ac7-4484-931c-057d28fccdda"}
